The Ukrainian parliament today rejected the request to abolish the paragraphs on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko had been sentenced, as part of a amendment to the Criminal Code.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned Minister of Foreign Affairs, was rejected by the MEPs at the second reading of the request to mitigate the penalties for economic offenses.
In October, Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for entering into an allegedly detrimental contract with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, in December the appeal of the convicts is to be tried in court.
Timoshenko himself describes the verdict as political revenge of the regime and also in the West the trial raised suspicions of bias of the court.
The request to remove paragraph 365, on the basis of which the Minister of Foreign Affairs was convicted, from the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 deputies.
226 votes would have been required for its adoption.
