Brand Story:
Innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If you wanted to search for a word that most accurately characterizes IBM’s strategy, it would probably be the word “longevity.”
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, known as a modern company, although a century has passed since its inception.
The basis for this longevity was already laid by its first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
Already he had the slogan that countless worldwide problems could easily be solved if people were willing to think a little bit.
His slogan "Think!" became the trademark for the future giant's life (and at the same time the title of the in-house magazine that IBM started publishing in 1935).
This was also the basis of Watsen’s thoroughly prepared corporate culture.
"For us from IBM, this long-term thinking means a continual movement towards the future.
IBM survived and was successful for a century because it remained true to its principles and did not shy away from changing everything else around.
This allowed us to transform technologies, business and society over the course of our first century.
We hope to do even more in the next hundred years,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company’s current director on the occasion of the anniversary.
Well-thought-out system
As early as the 1930s, Watson provided social care for his employees – in a similar way to the entrepreneur Ba<0xC5><0xA5>a in Czechoslovakia: the IBM people were one of the first American employees to have paid holidays, insurance by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as workwear and a well-designed remuneration system for the best innovators and dealers.
IBM’s long-term relationships with its customers are just as sophisticated.
The company was brilliant from the start in talent development - as one of the first companies worldwide IBM picked up any discrimination - and could choose accordingly.
Consistent with this anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan is for Palmisan to be replaced by a woman at the helm of IBM next year – Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years and has held the position of Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
IBM has been doing online brainstorming in recent years, which has led to many future strategies and innovations.
No wonder – there are plenty of ideas, almost half a million people are employed in the company.
An institution with a good reputation
Her unwavering position in the business guarantees the company a strong image, both internally and externally.
“From the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company,” said Economist, Harvard Business School professor and author of a book on IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems with the help of technology,” added George Colony of consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company itself emphasizes, it is a difference to be only present in the market or to form it directly through this presence.
IBM - called "Big Blue" in the states of its logo because of family, has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It’s one of the most versatile technology companies ever – IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consultation services across an incredible range of products – from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all the American technology companies, IBM owns the most patents and five of its employees have already been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His best-known inventions include ATMs, credit cards, financial swaps, barcodes and floppy disks.
With approximately $220 billion in market capitalization, IBM was the second-largest technology company (equal to Apple) this year, surpassing Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
The look ahead
Not all products and innovations met the tastes of today's customers - for example, the attempt with their own operating system OS/2, the online service Prodigy or the computers IBM PC jr.
“Business is based on the forward movement, so you can’t emotionally tie yourself to the past,” says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms – and if they don’t work, leave them too.
In contrast to the opponent Microsoft, which basically stands and falls with its operating system Windows.
Promising technologies
IBM’s profits are largely shared by services, software and hardware, each accounting for one-fifth of the company’s profits.
In 1990, hardware with a share of more than fifty percent was the most strongly represented.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion in low-profit assets, but at the same time it has invested $58 billion in the purchase of future-oriented technologies.
In these investments, IBM continues after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world like a storm for the first time.
Here, too, IBM remained faithful to the legacy of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who increased his investment in the midst of the Great Depression.
So far, it seems that the company IBM survives the current crisis unscathed.
The value of IBM shares has increased by 120 percent in a rocket-like manner since 2008, and the company’s net profit is growing continuously.
IBM’s corporate slogan is: everything can be changed – but not the values.
This is another reason why it can be expected that this flexible giant will also cope with the next crisis.
IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
The company IBM (International Business Machines), founded in New York a hundred years ago, initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was not adopted until 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch office in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later company IBM was laid by the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They owned technologies such as the famous lancing card clocks to register the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of rival firm Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
This leader then eclipsed even the founders of IBM - on Watson's ideas based to this day the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began manufacturing and selling all kinds of machines for the trade - from sausage and cheese cutters, to cash registers.
In the first four decades Watson led the company, he doubled its revenue to $9 million and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the executive chair for a full forty years, only then he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM engineers and computers helped guide flights into space – to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969, the famous flight of humans to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that defined the computer standard of that time was launched in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand it bought the consulting part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thereby fully entered the business with consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the “Smarter Planet” concept.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned so far, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and urban management.
In the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smarter Commerce” platform, which is designed to help merchants lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932, IBM founded a branch in what was then Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern European Headquarters is located in Prague and is also home to a world-class team of researchers working on voice recognition technology.
