Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies in the former <0xC4><0x8C>SSR: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at that time mainly only sold trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, in the West at that time only the chosen were allowed.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to Lake Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the trips to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (including the Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered trips to the west, but then you had to accept huge queues or sleep in a sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, the matter was far from over.
The so-called foreign exchange promise - the condition for an exit to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange commitment it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that continues to this day.
The velvet revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries all over the world last year.
A huge paradox, of which one is not even aware today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation was lifted in the neighboring Western European countries, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
When traveling to Paris, Czech holidaymakers slept in a tent in the park, because who would have had the money for an accommodation in a hotel or in a pension at that time.
A typical feature of trips abroad by Czechs at that time was a trunk full of canned food, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency freely.
Our standard of living and, as a result, our average salaries increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, after 1997, travel agencies began to prepare regular trips through charter flights, which made air travel incredibly cheap compared to the past thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the US, already had currency-free payments with all the advanced countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post- velvet" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was handled - to Thailand.
Since then, every year direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers fly to far-flung sunny countries; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
Around 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most highly developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than CZK 15 thousand per capita on a single holiday, including the costs at the resort.
