Europe's most beautiful pools
Jump into the blue
by Julia Stanek
Paddling pool in UFO optics, sumptuous pools in Budapest: If you travel through Europe, you can experience your blue wonder - and after a city tour or a hike, rest your tired legs in bubble baths.
A book shows where wellness in the water is best.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip in the past year and a half, one thing could not be missing in her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying back on the water, she looked up into elaborately designed domes, swam towards marble putties waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming pools.
If she liked a bath, she quickly took it into her notebook - with interesting details about the construction and history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools were explored by architecture historian Meder in this way - and now she presents them in her just published book "Badefreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore-Concrete Buildings" in the Taunus.
In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city each in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
With sports, she has not much on her mind, says Meder - only in the water is different.
Annoyingly, swimming fans have to put up with blue tiles and chlorine smell, while joggers can breathe in the beguiling scent of spruce forests or listen to cheerful bird chirping in the park.
“One day I wondered why swimming pools have to be so ugly,” says Meder, who lives in Vienna.
"So I started collecting nice baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Lapping in the plunge pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all the senses are served, says Meder.
And if the builders have made an effort, swimming pools can be a real feast for the eyes: "Instead of a floor, you have a water surface in bathrooms."
"On the one hand it is transparent, but on the other hand it reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything visually doubles: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
The small-format illustrated book "Badefreuden" conveys interesting information about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases on 190 pages - but above all makes you want to jump into the blue.
The pool collector Meder discovered remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing body of water in a quaint karst cave (cave in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a thermal bath whose pools are filled with alkali-containing water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (V<0xC3><0xA1>rosi Term<0xC3><0xA1>lfürdöny in J<0xC3><0xA1>sz).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: while you have the whole city in mind from the Zurich roof bath, you can look at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: In the steam bath there is a window from which you can observe the hustle and bustle on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in L<0xC3><0xA4>ngenfeld: the Aquadome <0xC3><0x96>tztal looks like a UFO just landed in the Alps.
It steams from three open-top shells in winter, while in the background the mountains of the <0xC3><0x96>tztal valley rise into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool, the pool collector Meder got the smell of chlorine in the nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulphur, in the <0xC3><0x81>rp<0xC3><0xA1>d bath in Békescsaba, Hungary, it smells so much of fuel oil that it is hard to believe you have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkaline-hydrocarbonate-containing healing water, which is almost black and whose silt sticks to your skin as soon as you slide into the pool - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful swimming spots: When she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing area in the Czech town of Luhatschowitz, she found a closed-off terrain.
The bathroom, designed by architect Du<0xC5><0xA1>an Jurkovic in 1902, has since been closed.
As Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds proliferating between the tiles.
However, the decline has been counteracted in a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
This bath has already undergone three phases of construction; you can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements dating from the time of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since its careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favourite pool of pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not only because it is originally from the Black Forest.
"It's an achievement to merge such different architectural styles into such a great unit," says Meder.
In such a palace, the dive in the thermal pool is apparently only a minor matter.
