Deutsche Bank to investigate raw materials business
by Christian Teevs
Is Deutsche Bank abandoning its agricultural commodities business?
According to SPIEGEL-ONLINE information, Josef Ackermann has commissioned a working group to examine the consequences of speculation for the poor of the world.
In January, the CEO wants to draw consequences.
Hamburg - Hamburg
According to a study, 84 percent of Germans find it unacceptable that banks speculate with agricultural raw materials such as wheat or corn.
Two-thirds of respondents even demand that Deutsche Bank and other credit institutions leave this business because it exacerbates the problems of the world’s poorest.
This is the result of a Forsa survey on behalf of the consumer organization Foodwatch.
The study is based on a report presented by Foodwatch in mid-October.
In it, the author Harald Schumann shows that the bets on the global commodity exchanges are driving up prices - and the banks are therefore complicit in the global hunger problem.
The campaign of the consumer advocates is directed specifically against Deutsche Bank CEO Josef Ackermann, even if major banks such as Goldman Sachs or Morgan Stanley act similarly.
Commodity bets were originally intended to hedge traders against price fluctuations.
But now most experts agree that the gamblers have decoupled themselves from supply and demand - and are making profits at the expense of the poorest.
