Ackermann, as the top bank lobbyist, is now particularly committed to the task.
“Deutsche Bank must remove all investments from its portfolio that use money to bet on food prices,” Bode said.
"Whether Mr. Ackermann is talking about people suffering from hunger or about the reputation of Deutsche Bank."
Ackermann’s insight comes as a surprise at first glance, but it is clear that the CEO wants to give a perfect picture a few months before he leaves office.
On Monday, Deutsche Bank announced that the Chief Executive Officer will not be joining the Supervisory Board as planned.
With a departure from the controversial agricultural speculation, he could improve his image.
And he hardly has to worry about any possible losses - after all, this would have to do with his successor.
