43 percent would advise acquaintances from such a bank, 49 percent said to think about canceling their account and switching to another institution.
21er Haus in Vienna
The Moved Pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and a happy ending: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion in Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and vanished.
It is now being re-opened as an exhibition hall.
When modern post-war architecture is swarming with clear shapes, glass halls, bold twists and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion by architect Karl Schwanzer is a striking and famous example for the 1958 Brüssler World Exhibition.
Schwanzer's pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still regarded as a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built the pavilion at the next world exhibition in Austria.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like outbuilding in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
Its pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, had been erected in the Swiss Garden near Vienna’s Südbahnhof, rebuilt and opened in 1962 a museum of the 20th century – the “20er Haus” (Twenty House).
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building has stood empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every way.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the <0xC3><0x96>sterreichische Galerie Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, a postdoctoral art historian with a considerable career, including in her youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, emphatically enforced the conversion among politicians and monument conservationists, she procured public funds and private sponsorship funds and determined the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there was to be a café and a bookshop, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krischanitz was the ideal cast for the performance.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich’s Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was an “extremely important place” for him, where he had looked at the exhibitions “almost every weekend”.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which had already lost its generosity and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and its conversion.
With the current conversion, there were far greater problems: The building was "an energy slur", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade were replaced, glass-fiber-reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel girders have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements brought room for the new use, a lowered light pit between the house and the street provides the exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red-brown anti-rust shade.
And the cinema room is still exactly as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also liked the monument protection office," says Krischanitz and points to a rough ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and modifications, the building has remained flexible and light.
It had been difficult with the pavilion, “which came from Brussels”, Krischanitz has recently said, a typical “drop-in-the-city story”.
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because an urban luck has occurred: Around the Swiss garden, the completely newly planned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier", with office and residential buildings, is currently being built.
And another stroke of luck may come: The 21er Haus could get reinforcement from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berlin Temporary Kunsthalle, and as you can hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighboring location in the Swiss garden.
