The scandal bank of Lake Zurich
The most adventurous bank in Europe is not located in Italy or France, but in Switzerland.
UBS almost went bankrupt in the financial crisis and has been sliding from one crisis to the next ever since.
Now it's up to a German to judge.
Axel Weber certainly didn’t think so.
After his spectacular departure from the top of the Bundesbank, it was announced in July that he would take on an almost as spectacular new job in 2013: Chairman of the Board of Directors of the Swiss major bank UBS - an unexpected and lucrative career move.
Axel Weber was publicly pleased, praised Switzerland for its beauty and UBS for its newfound solidity, and made friendly remarks about the future colleagues.
"UBS has made the turnaround".
"I look forward to working with Kaspar Villiger and Oswald Grübel".
But back in September, it became clear that everything would be completely different.
A UBS trader in London had bypassed all of the bank’s hedging systems and gambled around 1.7 billion euros.
UBS CEO Oswald Grübel, a banker not only famous in Switzerland, had to leave.
The Chairman of UBS’s Board of Directors has since also been struck down – and everyone is asking: When will Axel Weber finally arrive?
It has already been announced that Weber will be allowed to advise the bank from February 2012.
And he will take over the chairmanship of the Board of Directors in May - not just in 2013, as the bank announced on Tuesday.
This is going to be tough for Axel Weber.
He is not a banker, but rather an economics professor and central banker and would certainly have needed a training period.
At one stroke, he then assumes responsibility for the strategy of a bank that has just proven once again that it deserves the title of "Europe's biggest scandal bank".
On the one hand, UBS is huge – until recently it was the largest asset manager in the world – and on the other hand, it has been sliding from one scandal to the next for years.
Nothing, it seems, is spared the once-proud Swiss bank.
It started in the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
She had combined the image of the secretive and solid Swiss asset manager with ambitious goals: she also wanted to become a very big number in investment banking.
In 2007, UBS managed $1.6 trillion more money from high-net-worth clients than any other bank in the world.
And on the other hand, it had advanced as an investment bank into the league of the largest banks in the world.
That made an impression.
Hans Geiger, a former banker and later long-time banking professor in Zurich, says: "I always presented UBS to my students as a model of a good bank."
"From today's point of view, you ask yourself: How could I have been so wrong?"
He was greatly mistaken.
In 2007, it became apparent for the first time that something had gone horribly wrong in UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli surprisingly resigned, who until then was considered a highly intellectual and just as ingenious banker.
A few months later, he realized why he had left.
The bank’s investment division had been bogged down with subprime papers and had to write off billions.
To cope with this, UBS announced a capital increase of 13 billion Swiss francs.
For this, she actually found investors, but one that some would have raved about until recently: an opaque Asian sovereign wealth fund from Singapore and an Arab sovereign wealth fund that was so secret that you didn’t even know its name.
But that was only the first blow.
It got worse in April 2008.
The bank had to announce new losses of billions, and in 2006 Chairman Marcel Ospel, Switzerland’s second best-paid board member, resigned.
In October 2008, the disaster followed: UBS faced the collapse of its misinvestment in the financial crisis and had to be rescued by the state.
The SNB bought tens of billions of problematic securities from UBS, and the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for a compulsory convertible bond that allowed it to become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shaken - for she noticed how dramatic it is for a small country when it houses such large banks.
After all, UBS’s balance sheet total in 2007 was more than five times as large as Switzerland’s economic output (see chart).
“Once again, we could not save UBS,” says banking researcher Geiger.
The first disaster was followed by the second.
A few months later, UBS capitulated in the tax dispute with America and agreed to release the data of wealthy customers who may have evaded taxes with the help of the bank.
She also agreed to a payment of $780 million as a repayment of unjustified profits from these transactions, including a penalty.
Thus, UBS more or less openly admitted to having helped in tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in the competition for rich customers: the nimbus of secrecy.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was no longer the same.
This was followed by the resignation of the Chief Executive Officer and Chairman of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of client funds.
Within a few months, the bank had lost credibility in both core business areas: in investment banking through misspeculation and in asset management through tax evasion assistance.
And just as things calmed down a little, just when it was thought that UBS would be able to do it again, this unfortunate dealer story follows: A single dealer gambles 1.7 billion euros before the bank realizes that something is going wrong.
And it becomes apparent that risk management in investment banking is still not working.
"With the Adoboli case, we have found that risk control has changed too little," says Martin Janssen, an economist and professor of finance at the University of Zurich's Banking Institute.
The chief financial officer of a large German bank is also certain: "The problem with UBS is that it does not have control over risk."
It was precisely the idea of caution with which the Swiss bankers had long ago started to become guardians of the world’s great assets: no too great risks, but security for money – even beyond the Alpine republic the world might collapse.
The safes of the Swiss banks had become a symbol of unwavering reliability such as Lindt and Sprüngli for particularly noble chocolate.
The headquarters of UBS in Zurich still fits the cliché of the dignified Swiss private bank - it is only a bit larger.
Even the location is classic.
The bank is headquartered on Züricher Bahnhofstra<0xC3><0x9F>e, which leads directly from the main train station to Lake Zurich, which is framed by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are magnificent, the shop rents are among the highest in Europe.
Jewellers such as Tiffany's can be found here between traditional Swiss shops such as Confiserie Sprüngli.
Swiss banks have resided here for centuries: from the National Bank and the Palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Baer.
The UBS reception room is accessed through a heavy revolving door.
Inside, the walls are marble-clad, in front of them are thick leather armchairs, next to the bench logo a large sign for the "safe".
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has replaced both major Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, but at some point - or betray, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper, after all, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with the two major banks.
UBS has become much too big, he believes – especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons have also spread.
The Swiss have nothing more to say.
"And if they do, they have long since adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons."
In fact, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, brought it high profits and then the debacle: No European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the Swiss big bank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster became visible.
"On that Wednesday, the coalition government of the small seven million country decided on the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation," writes author Lukas H<0xC3><0xA4>ssig in his book "The UBS Crash".
Up to 68 billion Swiss francs, or around 45 billion euros, were approved by the politicians to save the large bank, which is facing bankruptcy.
How could it have happened?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem above all in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks merged into one giant corporation.
The result was a bank that was already too big for small Switzerland at the time of the merger - and continued to grow.
This helped to complement the two different predecessor banks of UBS: a rich but sleepy bank with a focus on asset management in Zurich and a poorer, but already more internationalised bank.
All of a sudden, the internationalized investment bankers came up with a lot of money that they could use to spin a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise: Peter Wuffli, CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
"I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team," says banking researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the high-intellectual, modest, who understands a lot about models and statistics, and Ospel, the belly man, who has worked his way up from the banking doctrine to the very top."
But Ospel finally relied on Wuffli.
And Wuffli probably made a decisive mistake in the end: "He thought his models were reality," says Geiger.
"This is a tragic case."
Tragic, maybe.
It is clear that there was a lot of overconfidence before the case.
UBS employees clearly remember the executive meetings where CEO Wuffli repeated the same slogan over and over again: toppling Goldman Sachs from the throne.
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
She led the League Tables, the rankings that documented the success of the banks of that time.
That's where UBS wanted to go, to the top.
A few steps had already been taken.
In the foreign exchange business and in stock trading, she played at the top.
However, business consultants who were hired highlighted a weakness: in the international interest rate business, in the banker's language "fixed income", there is a huge distance to the largest banks.
UBS has gaps in U.S. mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that almost cost them their existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a pre-established hedge fund invested in American subprime assets.
It developed into a huge machine that packaged and passed on securities on American mortgage loans – but also kept itself at risk.
Even when other banks have long sought an exit.
"Even in the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was on fire, UBS bought there," says banking expert Geiger.
So great the euphoria, so deep the case.
One manager after another had to leave when the attempts to clean up were more difficult than expected.
Posts at UBS have become a whirlwind seat and are shaky to this day.
Whoever runs the big bank now has an almost impossible job.
He needs to find a strategy for a bank that has lost all the obvious business models.
Banking researcher Geiger already has an idea: end of investment banking, focus on asset management, return to Swiss roots.
The bank doesn’t want to go that far (yet).
But investment banking is expected to shrink sharply, that much is already clear.
Next Thursday, the new bank boss Sergio Ermotti wants to present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Italo-Swiss was actually only intended as a transitional solution when the bank surprisingly separated from predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has prevailed: he is to manage the business of UBS permanently, said the Zurich Bank on Tuesday.
Ermotti plans to bring the investment bank back to its mid-1990s level.
3500 jobs will be eliminated.
But that will not be enough.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
How does she want to make money?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is already asking himself.
So far, he has only said publicly that he and his wife will first look for an apartment in Zurich.
Next year.
