Smart Crows Spread in Cities
In many places, seed crows are considered "problem birds": But the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of the cities, experts say.
Some like it, others want to get rid of it very quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities, residents complain about the dirt and noise of animals.
A remedy against the "problem birds" is not yet in sight.
Seed crows can no longer be gotten out of the cities, experts said at the first Crow Symposium in the East Frisian Leer.
There, experts from all over Germany discussed possible ways out.
You are looking for alternatives in the cities
Conservationists attributed the problems in cities to the rural exodus of the specially protected seed crows: The use of chemicals in agriculture is increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
Hunting, increasing cultivation and the felling of typical incubators made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected by nature.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs can be found in the Westphalian Soest, in the northwest in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen as well as in Leer.
In 2005, a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the county had caused negative headlines.
Critics had described catching the animals in bird traps and killing them with clubs as particularly brutal.
"The normal expulsion, the grumbling, does nothing," said Werner Klöver, a city and landscape planner from Leer.
Spraying nests with water or felling trees often has undesirable consequences, said the environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals dodge, large colonies split up and spread out in other places."
Only as an exception at hospitals, old people’s homes or schools is imaginable.
"We have to live with them, we can't get them away."
Without the surrounding area, the problem cannot be solved in the cities, said Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
A combination of greasing of the animals from sensitive living areas and baiting offers is conceivable, in order to resettle them in other places.
"Info boards instead of chainsaws", on the other hand, the psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens called for a completely different way of dealing with the animals: "After all, we can best bear a pimple on the face with confidence."
Jürgens had co-founded the Ascheberger Kr<0xC3><0xA4>hen-Lehrpfad in Schleswig-Holstein, where signposts inform about the life of the highly intelligent seed crows.
The project has already been adopted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on the criticism of the noise of birds: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say to each other."
The intelligence and dexterity of the animals are legendary: Seed crows not only use tools to get a treat, but even make their tools themselves as tools.
Behavioral researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested the intelligence of the birds on four seed crows.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to collapse a skeleton with stones in order to get to a moth larva.
Without much training, they determinedly realized what size and shape a stone must have to collapse the platform.
In a second attempt, the smart crows then had to solve a trickier problem.
In a vertically positioned cylinder, the researchers had placed a small bucket with a moth larva.
With the beak, the birds could not reach their prey.
However, the researchers had laid them pieces of wire.
From this all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket at the handle out of the tube.
Three of the four seed crows even managed to do this right away.
