Mass Slaughter on a Personal Level
A sensitive and generous start to Peter Englund's new book "Beauty and Terror: A Story of the First World War, narrated in Nineteen Fate" with a long list of main characters that goes to heart.
Here’s a tip on how to proceed: Cut this page carefully and make it your bookmark.
You will get to know these people very well in Englund’s novel-like narrative, and these main characters will function as your GPS, as a beacon in those few moments when you, like Englund’s, are lost men and women in the fog of war and deprived of your illusions.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He has written an unusual book, which he does not incorrectly describe as "a work of anti-history".
It contains few big names, important contracts or famous battles. There are hardly any ambassadors, frenzied reporters or discussions about tactics and equipment.
It is less a book about what happened, he explains, but more "a book about how it was". It is about "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Terror" is almost the war experience of 20 more or less inconspicuous men and women on both sides of the war together, from schoolgirls and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and office workers.
Some of these people become heroes.
Some become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go crazy or die.
Each of these lives flares up like the votive candles in a church, some are added, while others are extinguished.
Englund's book deviates from the usual history books.
It also corrects the notion that the First World War was only the devastating positional war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Terror" wanders with expert views over other war scenes: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book fall on beehives, one celebrates Christmas under the pyramids in Egypt, tsetse flies are an insoluble problem.
This is a moving book almost from the beginning.
The war floods the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a Hurricane Katrina that smells like Kordit.
Imagine you are a woman who is at home with her children and hears cannon fire in the distance. Are you staying or are you taking the flight?
Who's coming?
Hardly anyone understands what is happening or why this war is being waged at all.
"Missing facts," Englund notes, "have been furnished with assumptions, assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors."
"Beauty and Terror" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian Army, and Richard Stumpf, a young German ship's sailor.
Her stories were mainly taken from memories, letters and other material already published.
Their life stories can be frightening or poignant, but they are extremely vivid in Englund’s loss of detail collection of little moments.
Many of them deal with lack and help themselves.
In the story of a German schoolgirl, he tells: "Replacement, everywhere replacement."
"Replacement coffee, false aluminum, false eraser, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He tells more about the substitute meal in Germany.
He describes "meat made from pressed rice and baked in mutton fat (and most recently served with a false bone from wood), tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato skins, shoes soiled with wood."
There were, as he notes, “837 registered dietary substitutes allowed in the production of sausages, 511 registered coffee substitutes.”
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
One American recognizes his own urge for savagery and says of the war: “You feel that, despite everything, this is what was intended for men rather than to sit in the armchair, with the evening paper or the bestseller and a cigarette and a whiskey in hand, and to pretend that such a fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade means civilization and that there is no barbarism behind one’s own strengthened and battered shirt chest.”
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he will probably die and no one will take notice or care.
“If you distance yourself from the idea of sacrificing yourself, you want to think that this is happening in front of an audience,” he writes.
Instead, it’s as terrible as “a condemned man who was hanged in secret.”
Other observations are about the old Europe falling apart and about new kinds of terror.
“The conflict has increasingly become an economic competition,” Englund writes, “a war between the factories.”
He captures the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the bestiary of the still young century": "the word skillful and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a made-to-measure suit who slaughters while sitting behind a desk."
People behave in unforeseen ways, and there are frivolous behaviors as well as heroism.
Englund discusses the soldiers who actively tried to infect a prostitute with a venereal disease in order to escape the front line service.
"The grotesque expression of this can be discovered in the trade in gonococci, because soldiers bought and smeared themselves on their genitals, hoping to get to the hospital," he writes.
“Those who were really desperate rubbed him in the eyes, which made them blind for the rest of their lives.”
In this Swedish translation by Peter Graves, Englund’s poetry becomes supple yet unobtrusive and adapts perfectly to his human task.
In dozens of small scenes, he captures the way the war "uncontrollable forces unleashed in a unique way: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred."
People are starting to wonder why their leaders are making them fight.
The best books about the First World War were usually more falsified like Paul Fussell's "Great War and Modern Memory" or novels like Erich Maria Remarque's "Im Westen nichts Neues" than extensive history books.
Englund's band joins an unconventional hall of fame.
His book has the most devastating ending I've ever read in a non-fiction book.
I don't give it away anymore.
But it is as if he had snatched away this page with the main characters in front of us with his book and lit it with a match.
