A disaster exercise had taken place with a view of Zuccotti on Randalls Island.
Officials stepped up so-called chaos training – counter-terrorism measures, including the rapid relocation of a large number of police officers – to focus on Lower Manhattan.
The last training session took place on Monday night on the Manhattan side of the East River.
The order to move into the park came “at the last minute,” said someone familiar with the orders, which spoke of a declaration as “exercise.”
“The few policemen involved, to my knowledge, did not know that it was about Zuccotti Park,” said someone who wanted to remain anonymous.
"The only people who knew it was Zuccotti Park were the high-ranking officials of the resort."
One reason for the secrecy was a lesson the city had learned.
On October 14, officials wanted to clear the park, but then retreated when hundreds of protesters gathered after learning of these plans.
Officers from various police units were involved in Tuesday’s operation, including task forces from around the city—hundreds of mobile officers usually deployed in highly criminal neighborhoods.
Mr Kelly said that during the day, many people go in and out of the park, almost like commuters, so 1 a.m. is a good time to go in.
“It was appropriate to do this when the least number of people are in the park,” he said.
Ambulances with Jupiter lights and loudspeakers were ready for departure at Pike Slip and Franklin D. Roosevelt Drive near the Manhattan Bridge.
The lights and the pre-recorded messages that roared from the speakers seemed to intimidate many protesters.
When public officials entered the park in their light blue windbreakers, many protesters simply gathered their belongings and left the place.
Police said no tents would be touched until 1:45 a.m. to give protesters time to pack up their belongings.
Other teams of officials were seen gathering in the area to intervene should arrests become necessary in the park.
Reporters were forced to leave the park.
Paul J. Browne, spokesman for the police chief, said this was done for their own safety.
But many journalists claim that they were prevented from observing the police actions in the park, and they said that the handling of the officers was very rough.
Mr. Browne said that television cars could have taken pictures on Church Street on the west side of the park.
As the police moved westward through the protesters’ vast mess of personal belongings, including suitcases, artificial turf and bags of clothes, their city cleaning staff followed, picking up what had been left behind.
Some protesters who refused to go were dragged outside, and pictures of them appeared on the internet a short time later.
A main core of protesters took up position near the kitchen area of the camp in the center of the park.
Some built barriers and the police continued their methodical arrests.
About 10 people in the epicenter of the camp tied themselves together by their arms.
And two people chained themselves to trees, Mr. Kelly said.
Civil protection officials were called in to cut them loose.
As Mr. Kelly said, no arrests were made at the park until about 3:30 a.m.
According to police, the eviction was completed after 75 minutes.
Mr Browne said 142 people were arrested in the park.
Most arrests, he said, were due to “inappropriate behavior and resistance to arrest.”
The most prominent officer on the scene was Joseph J. Esposito, the head of the department, the highest uniformed official of the department.
Phil T. Pulaski, head of the criminal department, was also there.
Despite his presence, Mr. Kelly “did not lead the operation,” as Mr. Browne said.
In case they were to access, a second group of officials waited on the eastern side of Broadway, between Liberty and Cedar Street.
Barricades were built on Cortlandt Street, a block north of the park, and Pine Street, a block south.
It was possible to observe how from these locations the police extended the perimeter further and further around Zuccotti Park.
In one place, several officers, many of them with shields, were seen driving people outside.
About 28 people were in the northern area.
Some of the most violent actions of the night took place in the south of the park.
Around 5 a.m., a protester jumped onto the roof of a police vehicle south of Pine Street, and other demonstrators left the air out of the tire of a police bus.
In one place, the crowd threw a piece of plywood.
In the end, an official and a protester came to the hospital.
