Mission Ended, Congress Ready to Agree on Libya
In the end, it looks like Republicans and Democrats in Washington are already in agreement on the Libyan uprisings.
All that was needed was the success of the revolt, the arrest and murder of long-time dictator Muammar Gaddafi, and the end of American interference.
On Thursday, the Senate International Relations Committee passed a resolution under the direction of Chairman John Kerry (Massachusetts) along with Senator John McCain (Arizona) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Connecticut), praising Libya for the successful rebellion and the US troops for their "courage".
“This resolution honors the courageous people of Libya who have begun to rebuild their country,” Kerry said.
"It is a confirmation of the support of its democratic efforts by two parties."
The language may sound innocent, but so far nothing has been easy in the Libya debate.
This summer, lawmakers from both parties and the White House argued over the wording of a series of resolutions to approve or disapprove of the U.S. military’s role in NATO’s Libya mission.
In June, Kerry and McCain tabled a resolution authorizing the restricted use of U.S. military forces in Libya.
The bill was rejected in the Senate by a broad fringe group of both parties and there was no vote.
But on the same day, the bill was passed in the Senate, and the chamber overruled a decision to cut funding for American operations in Libya.
As a result, the U.S. mission fell into a kind of legislative purgatory – with a Congress that was upset enough to criticize Obama’s approach to the mission, but not angry enough to finally pull the floor under his feet.
Then the indecisiveness of Congress was overtaken by the events.
Tripoli fell to Libyan rebels in August and Gaddafi was killed on October 20.
The NATO mission officially ended on October 31.
Perhaps the Senate is ready to act.
The resolution of the Committee on International Relations "congratulates the people of Libya for their tremendous courage and extraordinary perseverance in their self-liberation" and "praises the men and women of the U.S. military and their coalition partners who support military operations to protect the people of Libya, for their extraordinary courage and professionalism."
The resolution also reaffirms “the national interests of the United States in a successful and irrevocable transition of Libya to democracy.”
Will the new measures receive full support from the Foreign Relations Panel, or will they divide legislators, as the June law did?
The final version meets the resistance of Senator Richard G. Lugar (Indianapolis), the top Republican of the committee.
Lugar’s spokesman said Monday that he had not yet seen the final version of the new law.
According to Capitol, it’s up to the Senate to vote this week on a constitutional amendment that calls for a balanced budget, a top priority in nearly every congressional legislature of Republicans and some Democrats.
The measures, led by Republican Bob Goodlatte (Virginia), will be the first constitutional amendment to the budget or any other area that is currently coming to a vote in the Senate or Congress.
Other legislators have tried unsuccessfully to bring their amendments to the vote, even though they have tried often enough.
Goodlatte’s amendment is just one of 68 constitutional amendments submitted to this Congress that cover a whole range of issues.
Some are double – the same law was presented to both Congress and the Senate – others differ only slightly from each other.
There are at least 15 versions of the balancing budget change in the Senate alone and another dozen that would “control federal spending.”
Some of the laws are also identical, but they give their principals — especially beginners among Republicans who want to polish up their resume — the opportunity to brag about having “written” such a measure.
The Budget Control Act, passed in August, requires both the Senate and Congress to vote on a change in the budget balance.
In March, 58 senators voted in favor of a non-binding resolution supporting the idea of such an amendment.
Beyond the budget, some members want to limit the number of provisions that members of Congress can submit, while Republican José E. Serrano (New York) wants to lift the limit to two terms of the president.
Republican Jesse L. Jackson (Illinois) has proposed a number of changes that include guaranteeing the right to good education and health care.
A change that prohibits same-sex marriage, as well as a change that prohibits the burning of flags, is a recurring template.
Some legislators also want to allow the repeal of federal laws if two-thirds of the states reject them.
As eager as the members propose changes, they move as much faster as in previous years.
In the 111th Congress, legislators submitted 77 such amendments. in the 110th Congress 66.
The pace is fading compared to that of the early 1990s, when members regularly proposed more than 150 changes every two years, according to the figures provided by the Senate Library.
But they were also not much more successful than today.
The last amendment to be added - the 27th - was ratified in 1992, but was actually proposed to Congress as early as 1789.
