This week, on November 18, Lyman and 27 other current and former military employees anxiously await a trial with a historic hearing in Arlington, Virginia, to decide whether to allow a lawsuit they filed against former Defense Secretary Robert Gates and his predecessor, Donald Rumsfeld, to go to court.
The lawsuit alleges that Gates and Rumsfeld did not take action against the widespread rape within the military and in violation of the soldiers’ constitutional rights.
Filed in February by Susan Burke, a lawyer from Washington, D.C., the lawsuit initially comprised 17 plaintiffs, but rose to 28 in the following months: 25 women and three men, all claiming to have been raped or sexually assaulted by fellow soldiers, and that the military failed to investigate, convict, or provide appropriate justice after the alleged assault.
Burke says she is pursuing the top military leadership as the problem begins there.
“The military is hierarchical,” she says.
"Who are the individuals who are in a position to exterminate the culture's retribution? The leadership."
Burke also says she has contacted nearly 400 other survivors since February, many of whom could be part of future lawsuits.
Their strategy: Instead of all the plaintiffs putting their eggs in a basket, so to speak, they will, if necessary, file many more lawsuits to maintain the pressure.
The Defense Department’s defense team, led by federal prosecutor Neil MacBride, has filed a motion to dismiss the lawsuit.
The files of the court, which are available to Newsweek, detail the defense strategy, primarily that the military cannot be charged by current or former soldiers for injuries that have occurred in the armed forces.
Due to a 1950 Supreme Court Act, the so-called Feres Doctrine, the government is not liable for injuries inflicted on soldiers in active service.
"The alleged damage occurred during the plaintiffs' military service," the document says.
The Department of Defense refuses to comment on this story.
Things have changed since the 1950s.
If women are still not allowed to serve in combat, the distinction lies solely in the name: modern wars rarely have clear fronts.
In both Iraq and Afghanistan, teams of female soldiers play increasingly important roles, especially in contact with local women in the war zones.
The result: between these two wars, 150 female soldiers died, two-thirds of them in combat.
It’s time to modernize the military, Burke says.
And she is not alone in her struggle: three more complaints besides her are pending.
At Yale Law School, the Veterans’ Legal Services Clinic is preparing a lawsuit against the four major military academies for allegedly promoting a misogynistic atmosphere.
Independently, the non-profit Vietnam Veterans of America collects a lawsuit against the military focusing on the diagnosis of “personality disorder” that rape victims received in order to dismiss them from service — a common practice according to activists such as Anu Bhagwati of the Service Women’s Action Network, a human rights group.
Her group filed a lawsuit against the Veterans Administration in December, accusing her of discriminatory practices in her handling of benefits claims for individuals who claimed to have been sexually abused in the service.
Nine laws were presented to Congress independently by a mix of senators and representatives of both parties, which provide a number of clues.
In 2010, according to the Department of Defense's Sexual Assault Prevention and Response Office, 3,158 sexual abuse cases were reported.
But most abuses are not reported at all, and according to the Pentagon’s own estimate, this figure accounts for about 13.5 percent of the estimated 19,000 cases that occur each year.
The report, published in March, also examines law enforcement rates: in 2010, 20 percent of the cases recorded in the military came to court, only half as many as in civil law.
The plaintiffs in Burke's case describe their attacks as just the first of a series of traumas.
In Lyman’s case, she reported the alleged rape to the military police less than an hour after the robbery.
That night, she says, she was asked 11 times to tell the details of her rape to a whole host of police officers, doctors, and commanders.
She had a rape kit and the blood of her attacker, which came from a cut on his arm, was found in her bed.
Six months later, in April 2009, Lyman was heard by a judge, during which she was asked about the sex she had before assaulting her boyfriend.
Six people testified as character witnesses in the name of the alleged perpetrator, who was ultimately acquitted.
“I still remember the day the verdict was read out,” Lyman says.
"I thought the contractions would start. I ran screaming out of the courtroom."
"They took me to the psychiatric ward and I remember when I came out again, I said to my commander, 'This wasn't his procedure, this was my procedure.'
Lyman was asked to see a military psychiatrist who eventually diagnosed a personality disorder and declared her incapacitated.
In January 2010, she was dishonorably discharged, so she receives no support whatsoever.
Whether the lawsuit filed by Lyman and the other plaintiffs is progressing is pure speculation, says John Turley, a professor of law at George Washington University Law School.
Still, he notes, "In my view, they should be moving forward."
What stands between them and a verdict is this doctrine that has been criticized since it was first questioned.
I am a lifelong critic of the Feres doctrine.
The military is a decade behind, because they don’t have the same incentive and the same deterrent that comes with liability.
He adds, “The odds are against them... but it’s important for them to try.”
These things will only change if good people are willing to fight.
If the hearing doesn’t follow her path, Burke, the plaintiffs’ attorney, will start with her hundreds of other plaintiffs for future cases.
“We will continue to fight the military in this regard until reforms are made,” she says.
Or until we die, whatever comes first.
Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who sent their anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who has confessed to committing murder in a July shooting in Norway that killed 77 people, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time in front of his computer until his attack and chatted with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social networks.
After this summer’s tragedy, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It's easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
“We found that it wasn’t hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British ideas factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding place of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply need to use the site’s advertising tool to pinpoint their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy — just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of right-wing extremist groups across Europe and then targeted them with add-ons, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the add-ons invited users to a survey asking about their level of education, their attitude toward violence, and their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters of 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries – without even having to leave their offices once.
“It’s a fairly new research method,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online promoters of right-wing extremist groups are mostly young, male and resentful of immigration.
But in a sort of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, democratic, and less violent than those who remain seated behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to society trends like in “likes,” text messages, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, Facebook’s “data supernova” is generating a research boom that has seen the number of scientific papers with the name of this page in the title increase by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that through this page you can study people you don’t normally reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you used to try to interview people from the British National Party, it was very hard to identify them."
“They had to inform the party first and it would never have allowed them access,” Bartlett says.
“With Facebook, all that falls away — you go straight to them.”
Others say that the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their binge drinking on Facebook were significantly more prone to problem drinking than students who were silent about this topic.
Moreno suggests that peer-level students, such as residential consultants, monitor the site and help a student if they post too many status updates.
“You can’t solve a problem if you haven’t recognized it,” Dimitri Christakis, Morenos co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle, told the Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who otherwise would not have been found."
Facebook also constantly taps into the data of its own population.
The site’s data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, voter turnout at the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (primarily using information that only Facebook has access to – champions of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its large data finder accessible to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want to or not, and to be able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to release its own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, anything is allowed online.
“I don’t think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study in which he examined students’ public pages on Facebook.
"As far as she's concerned, it was just about her and her friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant will be absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information in a user profile and in posts is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There is no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research has to take care of the social – and a lot of social life is still going offline.”
‘Cold and inhumane’: Anders Behring Breivik to appear before a public court for the first time
