7 Lessons From The Interview With The Late Steve Jobs Shown In A Theater This Week
After Steve Jobs’s death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting the tech genius as a great modern inventor.
But what Apple fans may find most revealing in the recently rediscovered Jobs interview, which was dusted off this week before special film screenings in key markets, is how much this creative head has understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and self-proclaimed hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer who diligently tinkered with charts—a man who believed that many business owners suffer from “a disease of thinking that a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work... [but] there’s a tremendous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Idiots" about the breakup of the personal computer. And he sat with Jobs for more than an hour, in which they had one of the rare, detailed conversations.
By this point, 10 years had passed since Jobs had been pushed out of Apple, and he was already working hard on his new computing company, NeXT, looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley’s interview was used in expert idiots, he says the interview’s copy templates were missing from delivery.
It wasn’t until after Jobs’ death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director’s garage.
This slightly revised footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which comes to the Landmark Theatre this Wednesday and Thursday.
To someone known for loathing in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In the course of the interview, there are four times longer breaks between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of reflection in which jobs clearly weigh their thoughts and strive for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs’s perfectionism comes to light when he seems impatient with Cringely’s questions and spurs him to respond more quickly to themes or sub-plots of greater importance.
Recorded before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, the Lost Interview somehow seems eerily far-sighted when Jobs evaluates what other companies think is right or wrong and represents his own vision of the future of the computer.
It’s one thing to read Jobs’ posthumous tributes to his career, but to see Jobs here as the eager dreamer on the verge of greatness is something very different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Shortly after he had done all this here, he set out and did it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a company:
"During all the years in business, I always ask, "Why are you doing things?". And the answer you always get is, "Oh, that's just how it's done."
Nobody knows why he does what he does. No one in the business really thinks about things in depth.
That's what I found out.
Jobs is continuing his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Astonished at how costs were recorded—mostly starting with “standard costs” that were guessed at and then adjusted with “deviation”—he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined down to the smallest detail.
How the Pope was praised:
Jobs tells of the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to sneak into the telephone company and make long distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Job’s enthusiasm when he describes the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is contagious.
He describes how Wozniak and he would test the box by using a toll phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while looping through as many satellites as possible.
“We sent stuff around the world a half-dozen times and when you yelled into the phone, it came out a minute later in the phone next door,” Jobs says, giggling.
“We were young and we learned that we can build something ourselves that can control trillions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We both, we didn't know much, but we were able to build this little thing that can control a giant thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don't think there would be Apple without it.
Jobs goes on to tell of a glorious prank that Wozniak and he nearly pulled off when they called the Vatican via Blue Box in the middle of the night and wanted to talk to the Pope as much as they could to imitate Henry Kissinger.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were called in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two had to lash out before the Pope himself came to the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and unpreparedly called Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
"That had a remarkable impact on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views on what a company was and how well it treated its employees."
Later, Jobs became one of the HP employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
He was as big as a suitcase, had a small screen with Braun's tube, and I fell in love with him.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang on to this machine and write programs for them.
How to improve innovation:
Several times in the interview Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he built in some boards, he was asked by a customer to assemble the whole computer.
He worked with a payment period of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and the delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple, he recalls the problems he had with developing a computer mouse:
"I remember resounding arguments... They yelled at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could have built for $15. That was incredibly believable.
About large companies that decline:
Long before he revived Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled with their visions and lost control of their stocks.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so make a better copier or printer, so what?"
They own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [are] those people who ultimately lead the businesses and the product that pushes people out of decision-making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is eradicated by people who have no concept of good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship is necessary.
This happened with Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
You could have been ten times bigger if Microsoft had been in the 1990s.
You have won the defeat of victory.
About Innovation as an Art Form:
“There’s a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop this great idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about your finesse.
You have to make votes, certain things you can't, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5,000 things, these concepts, and bring them all together...
Ultimately, it boils down to taste, it boils down to trying to deal with the best stuff people have created, and then trying to bring those things together into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who work there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happen to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn’t for the computer industry, they’d be doing fantastic things in other areas.
Scalia and Thomas dine with opponents of health laws as court accepts case
On the day the Supreme Court gathered behind closed doors to discuss the politically divisive question of whether to hear a challenge to President Obama’s health laws, two of its judges, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, attended a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will represent the case in court.
The incident took place last Thursday when all nine judges met for a meeting to discuss the petitions for consideration.
One of the cases to be dealt with was a lawsuit filed by 26 states against the sweeping health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that became a buzzword among conservative activists across the U.S.
In fact, a 5 1/2-hour basic discussion is expected in March, the outcome of which is likely to fuel the 2012 presidential campaign, which will be in full swing at the time the court decision is announced.
The lawyer who will stand trial and claim that the law is toppling is likely to be Paul Clement, once Attorney General under the administration of George W. Bush.
Clement’s firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of almost two dozen companies that supported the Federalist Society’s annual dinner, a long-established group dedicated to defending conservative legal principles.
Another company that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the business associations, the National Federation of Independent Business, that are challenging the law.
Another sponsor was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which is heavily financially involved in the outcome of the process.
The dinner took place a few hours after the court had deliberated on the case at a Washington hotel.
Among others, Mitch McConnell, the leader of the Republican faction in the Senate and a declared opponent of health care reform
The guests of the dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
This is nothing new: the two judges have been attending events of the Federalist Society for years.
This does not violate moral rules.
In fact, judges are exempt from the code of conduct that governs the actions of lower federal judges.
If they were, they would probably fall under Principle 4c of the Code, which states: "A judge may participate in benefit events of the law nearer and other organizations, whereby the judge may not be a speaker, guest of honor or, according to the program, a guest of such events."
Nevertheless, the extreme proximity of Scalia and Thomas to two of the law firms associated with the case, as well as to a company with a massive financial interest in it, was enough to alert morale and government activists.
“This startling break with morality and the contrary to the Code is a lie to some judges’ lawsuits, the court is following the same rules that apply to all other federal judges,” said Bob Edgar, president of the Common Cause, a civil rights movement in the United States.
"The judges won and dined during a benefit event with lawyers with pending proceedings in court."
Their appearance and support of a fundraiser for this event undermines any claim to impartiality and is not acceptable.
Scalia and Thomas show little consideration for critics who say they mix court matters too easily with groups guided by the agenda, such as the Federalist Society.
And Thomas' wife Ginni is a well-known conservative activist.
On the other hand, the conservatives claim that it is Judge Elena Kagan who has a moral problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan was an attorney general under the Obama administration when the first lawsuits came to trial in the first instance.
Her critics urged Kagan to withdraw herself from the case hearing because she was too involved in defending the law to be unbiased.
Kagan does not make any arrangements to do so.
