Pentagon Urgent Warnings of Possible Defense Cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta fueled Congress on Monday when he warned that automatic budget cuts would undetectably weaken national security, triggering a financial chain reaction from the Pentagon’s halls to the war scenes in Afghanistan and civilian assembly lines.
The Pentagon is already thinking through cuts of $450 trillion over the next decade, but now fears that further cuts of $600 trillion or more will be necessary if Congress can’t make a cut in spending.
“The impact of these cuts would be devastating for the Department,” Panetta wrote in a letter to Republican Senators John McCain, Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, South Carolina.
He said a failure of Congress to reach a budget agreement, which will lead to a so-called confiscation, would lead to 23% general cuts as well as a halt to numerous new projects.
“Such a high cut, carried out in such a thoughtless manner, would make most of our ship and construction projects unfeasible — you can’t buy three-quarters of a ship or a building — and seriously harm other modernization efforts,” Panetta wrote to the senators.
“We would also be forced to involuntarily separate from a large part of our civilian personnel and, as the reduction would be implemented so quickly, we would almost certainly have to leave civilians on leave in order to reach the target.”
"These changes would destroy the faith of those who maintain our military and seriously damage our alertness."
The cuts were ultimately going to hit the combat troops,” Panetta said.
“While wartime contingents in the anti-terrorist fight are not directly affected by the seizure, the serious interference with the basic budget would adversely affect war efforts,” Panetta warned.
"Personal attitudes were cut, which would lead to delays in attitudes and the attitudes oversight that support the war."
“Staff’s salaries would be cut, leading to late payments to wartime traders, and legal as well as political support would be disrupted.”
The two senators responded to Panetta 10 days ago, asking for more details about the potential impact of the automatic cuts on the Department of Defense.
"The consequences of a seizure by the Department of Defense would usher in a rapid decline of the United States as the world's leading military power."
"We are vehemently opposed to this draconian act," the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon when they published Panetta's letter.
"This is an outcome we cannot live with, and it is certainly not one that should be imposed on us."
“The seizure is a threat to the national security interests of the United States and its entry should not be permitted.”
Whether Panetta’s letter and the new warnings from the senators will increase the pressure on a compromise in the budget or reinforce demands to exempt the Pentagon from cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has increasingly bluntly expressed the potential cuts, though he has had many years of experience with the budget in Congress and the White House before he came to the top of the Pentagon, and knows he faces tough decisions.
At a press conference last week, the Secretary of Defense painted a grim picture of what might be ahead – a military with shell but no core.
"It's a ship without sailors."
"It's a brigade without ammunition."
"It's an Air Force squadron without enough trained pilots."
