How to Uncover a Lie
A look at the current headlines shows how questionable and widespread deception and lies are in daily life.
The Republican presidential candidate, Herman Cain, is busy coping with allegations of sexual harassment on the part of several women, and both sides accuse each other of lying.
Penn State’s leadership has been accused of perjury for allegedly withholding reports that a retired football coach sexually abused boys.
Last week, an open microphone was heard when French President Nikolas Sarkozy claimed to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were very quickly refuted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in the Oval Office.
Stories of cheating at school and at college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents in which teachers have given their students the exam answers so that they themselves are well-versed in their performance reviews.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lying and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
Many of these lies are considered to be false.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing lies or “uncovering lies” is one that is important for every person to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game, such as charades, where the goal is to shout “Have you!”, exposing a deception is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have conducted far-reaching research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been exposed.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don’t always stutter, stammer, blush, and fidget.
However, one cannot infer from this that these liars are difficult to uncover and expose.
An experienced liar can penetrate to the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, about questioning and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the vast and ever-growing field of exposure, and it is clear that exposing a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to find our way around our complex world, especially when hiring or interviewing people or negotiating or managing is part of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at appreciating other people, pique their interest, and master their own emotions, and they intuitively sense how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men are more likely to tell "self-centered" lies than women whose lies are more "orientated" - usually they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly "fat lies").
We also know that when a person has been exposed as a malefactor, others feel less guilty of lying to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
This is called baselining, the starting position.
It provides a reference point for later evaluation of changes.
Observe the posture, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
You should know better when someone usually trips with their foot all the time, so they don’t wrongly blame him for tripping with their foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and non-verbal behaviors.
Think of these agglomerations as alarm bells ringing, not as evidence of exposure.
People who cheat may freeze when they try to remember their story, maybe their feet point toward the door, or they lean toward the exit, change their position in significant ways, or show a “relaxation after the interview,” this deep, relaxing exhalation, and the shift in attitude when all the hard questions are over.
Questioners often erroneously signal that a job interview is over, just to keep an eye out for that relaxation after the interview.
Also, pay attention to the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson’s slip-up is famous for using the past tense when he claimed his wife was still alive and sparked a national search for her.
Deceptive people can also use a distancing language: "I didn't have a sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question altogether.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when answering a tricky question: "Well...to tell you the truth...as far as I know...to the best of my knowledge."
This makes the answer more perceptive than factual, which often causes the alarm bells to ring.
There is no magic tool for unmasking lies, but you can learn skills that allow you to unmask.
Thanks to these skills, anyone can become a victim of fraud less often, both in private and in professional life.
