The quintet included Costa Rica in its tour to celebrate its 20th anniversary
"Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam’s bassist Jeff Ament says the band is prepared to give one of their best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
They were expected for more than 20 years, but the band assures that a dream will come true for them when they play in Costa Rica.
The group’s bassist and co-founder, Jeff Ament, gave Viva an exclusive interview from Brazil last week.
The band is in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary and on Sunday the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On this day they perform at the National Stadium from 7.30 pm together with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You can read an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in the online edition of La Naci<0xC3><0xB3>n.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream comes true when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what this means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true for us.
This is just the second time we’ve played in South and Central America, and so far it’s been great.
I have only been to Costa Rica once for a holiday. It is such a beautiful country that we will definitely stay there for a few more days.
It’s exciting for us to bring our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are completely devoted. They experience the days before the concert intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry to have taken so long to get here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Isn’t that a bit of pressure from your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve put on in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played a couple of huge shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play there.
We love this country, we love surfing and we love the jungle. Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world for this.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua. Together with Mexico, these are excellent areas for surfing. In this way, we learned about people who love surfing.
With a view of the tour you have offered giant shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there, we also set no limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
What's up?
I think that’s partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs, and everyone likes a different song, so it’s not easy to decide which one we’re going to play.
If we add two or three songs that we haven’t played in a while, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs, otherwise they might be forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I think, therefore also for the audience.
With this tour you celebrate your twenty-year history.
When you look back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
For starters, I don’t think any of us have imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years, and it looks like a dream.
We continue to count on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are excited to create music.
We are lucky to be able to travel to places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean to you to have actively participated in the birth of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great bands.
We are good friends with the people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and quite unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Every now and then a band emerges from a city, but it is unusual for five or ten groups to come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We’re still happy to be friends with them all and we’re honored to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It is also very unusual for a band like yours to have stayed together with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago. That alone is much more time than many bands survive.
First of all, I believe that we are all lucky to still be alive and we take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give every individual the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and his music. We couldn't be better off.
Your relationship with glory has not always been easy, but thanks to your success, you have always been able to do what you wanted.
How do you find balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often because it’s too easy to fall in love with this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you remember that people came for the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it has brought to life, without being obsessive about being a famous rock star.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and it was great in the beginning.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who built the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh together and talk about music and football and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and therefore chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos of several groups and we liked this band the best. So we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. This will certainly be exciting.
Why do you change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter every time you play live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influenced you as a bassist?
From so many+
Among the first to come to my mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fad?
I think we all don't feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone else that came up at the same time. If they’re still important today, I think that’s great because it’s worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever.
At first her music was darker, now she is more positive.
What's up?
That's interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a bit frivolous, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive about them.
Both of them shed tears when I heard Ed play them, they're very dark songs.
I believe that as you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life - for example, if you lose a family member or a friend - it affects your artistic work and your music and these two songs clearly embody that for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
