Secretary Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come gives details of the plane crash that killed Secretary of State Francisco Blake and seven others.
The Secretar<0xC3><0xAD>a de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat for Communications and Transport in Mexico) informed that the results of the investigation into the accident, in which the government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and another seven people were killed, indicate that the helicopter with its whole intact structure directly hit the ground without the pilot being able to initiate an emergency landing.
Speaking at a press conference, Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before take-off that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wings at 25 meters height had contact with trees, with the helicopter losing the fuselage, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for transporting personnel.
He also said that no helicopter parts were found during the investigations in the area where the plane had come down.
"No aircraft parts were found elsewhere during the search, the impact affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has an inclination of 7 to 30 degrees.
At the moment, the priority is to get the results as soon as possible, but this could take several months, maybe even a year.
For his part, Gilberto L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Meyer, General Director of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Auxiliary Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter had flown from the Estado Mayor Presidencial on impact at cruising speed and the aircraft had fallen onto a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of the impact."
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, listed six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with the flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of visual flight, which means that the crew must have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
During the onward flight towards the border area between Mexico City and Mexico State, some low-hanging clouds were raised.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that the team had chosen a lower area with better visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
Impact point:
The impact coordinates and the last radar record of the helicopter are the same, and there may have been no loss of control of the aircraft or deviation from the flight path prior to the impact.
Dispersal of the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available to date indicates that the helicopter had collided from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered remnants of the aircraft suggests that the helicopter with its undamaged structure had hit the ground.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft do not indicate fire or explosion at the scene of the accident.
The latest results indicate several ground contacts.
During the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is sloping and has an inclination of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a meticulous search in an area that went beyond the restricted area at the scene of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, reinforcing the assumption that the intact aircraft structure had collided with the ground.
MSS Announces Research Protocol to Find the Gene for Obesity
The Social Security Institute of Mexico is leading a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, which is supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexico Social Insurance Institute) announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for childhood and adolescent obesity under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence", with which to find the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, head of the Unidad de Investigaci<0xC3><0xB3>n Médica en Bioqu<0xC3><0xAD>mica (Department of Medical Research, Focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutrition specialists and social workers has been established.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate program at the Instituto Nacional de Salud P<0xC3><0xBA>blica (INSP) and the Centro de Investigaci<0xC3><0xB3>n y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to take part in the study. Interested parties can come to the IMSS sports fields in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are carried out every Saturday from 8.00 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation began on the sports field of Cuauhtémoc (in the west of the state of México) and continues since October 8 on the sports field of Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt (in the east of the state of México).
When the target of 500 to 600 investigators is reached, the study will be continued on the sports field of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and completed on that of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to learn about the factors and role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the World Diabetes Day, he stated that the aim was for three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 years to complete nutrition-related questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They will also be asked questions about their physical activity and family history of disease to control risk factors that could result in diabetes or kidney failure.
He further stated that on the Saturdays mentioned, the study subjects were measured (weight, size, waist circumference), their blood pressure was controlled and blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (attempt to identify genes associated with childhood obesity) were determined.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez stressed that this study was being carried out in response to the concerns of health workers about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys conducted in 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent, while obesity also increased dramatically," said the IMSS specialist.
He stated that the search for genetic markers is justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico is different from that of other peoples.
He stated that an average Mexican is 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European, and 5 percent African, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn off the excess of energy (calories) consumed so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the study participants would be a comprehensive study of the children, which would determine whether they had a degree of overweight or obesity.
It would even examine the occurrence of dark skin folds in the neck and inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and pre-stage diabetes.
All information would be kept confidential and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors. The doctors explain to the parents all the measurement results and suggest to them lifestyle changes that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three basic factors responsible for overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, that is, lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport, instead of walking short distances.
The high caloric intake, i.e. an increased consumption of sugared beverages and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake, as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM, developed polymer-modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If attention were paid to the signs emanating from the road surface, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200 000 potholes if the rainy season breaks out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (urban area of the Valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warning and assuring that even the laying out and maintenance of the potholes will be significantly reduced.
In his talk "Technical Impact Holes", given on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera felt that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the occurrence of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphaltene - and the other part a low - the so-called malthene. Together, they give the road surface its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
Tough-elastic behavior of asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very viscous and at 50°C it is almost solid, while at very low temperatures it becomes brittle.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in a day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer explained.
The FQ researcher noted that the majority of streets in Mexico City have a flexible road surface composed of six layers of material, the last three of which contained asphalt.
Between the top layers is a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer had been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Above the wear layer," he explained, "a final layer is laid, the so-called base layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it must produce friction.
The one that receives and distributes the most forces, the base layer also needs a reasonable thickness and the material of which it is made must be maintained.
Weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially water,” he said, “because it significantly affects the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes wet, water penetrates the layer and escapes only with difficulty, causing a softening of all layers of the road surface and, as a result, the appearance of potholes.
When a pothole is created," he said, "the top layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load is another important cause of potholes, so the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be proportional to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is adhered to in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be repaired easily and without using high temperatures.
