Such was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last November 4th, a lophoscopist from the Cali Public Prosecutor’s Office (CTI) who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia – Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia) said: “Alfonso Cano” by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists in the CTI department, Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez was on standby this week, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez worked in communities of Choc<0xC3><0xB3>, where he often had to spend five days in the jungle to reach the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the required courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin that is exposed to friction, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
In the week of the operation against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was instructed to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he flew by helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he was supposed to identify two bodies, and that it was suspected that one could be that of the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was to take the ten-finger print sheet of Guillermo Le<0xC3><0xB3>n S<0xC3><0xA1>enz (his actual name).
However, when he reached the place where the body was with the examination, he could not identify it because of its physical appearance, because this was not in the least similar to the pictures he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a peasant in the area, wore no glasses, and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a trowel and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body to those on the print sheet.
He had seen correctly: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, this Puerto Tejada-born man was in charge of telling the defense minister, Juan Carlos Pinz<0xC3><0xB3>n, that he was indeed the head of the FARC.
Searching for clues
For a dactyloscope from the Sij<0xC3><0xAD>n in Cali, the tribute given by President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez at a press conference on the use against "Cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in the resolution of a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify corpses, they also support investigations into murder and robbery cases and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When they are arrested, many offenders present false identity documents or they do not have one.
We'll take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher told us that in the event of a theft, he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house, because the thief had supported himself with his hand exactly at this point, when he pulled out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for taking fingerprints. But in this case, we were able to take the impression of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
The fingerprints can also be used to exonerate or burden murder suspects.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
During the investigation, it was suspected that a family member might be a suspect, and in fact, a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, it is linked to the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that “the fingerprints were taken from the object with chemical or physical reagents.”
When they appear, a planting trowel or tape is used to take them along.
After that, the prints are sent to the asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil registry.
“The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identity papers,” said the expert from the CTI.
He said that not everything is as it is depicted in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything that glitters is gold, not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if a corresponding comparison is made.
The “outrages” challenge the authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters crowded into tents in Zuccotti Square.
A large part complied with the eviction order and changed its location to a nearby park.
Members of the Ocupy Wall Street movement challenged New York authorities this Tuesday as they tried to re-enter Manhattan Square with a court order after being cleared of the square at dawn and attempting to occupy another place on the Big Apple.
Hundreds of demonstrators crowded in front of Zuccotti Square, seeking to gain access to it with a court order that allowed the "outraged" to re-camp at the site, while another part of the movement complied with the eviction order and occupied a park further north in the city, where nine were arrested.
"Our idea is that if the court doesn't allow us to camp on the square, we'll meet in another place and continue the battle with legal means to return to the Zuccotti, with sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations," said Mark Bray, one of the Ocupy Wall Street movement's spokespersons.
Bray explained that the "outrageous" response to the eviction of their tent camp, which had been ordered directly by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg, came to court where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forcible eviction of the square and allowing protesters to camp.
In addition, the "Indignants" occupied a new park located at the intersection of centrally located Canal Street and Sixth Avenue very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel connecting New York and New Jersey and owned by Trinity Church.
They were able to occupy the place for at least an hour, but then the police arrived and arrested some of the protesters, although Bray can not give exact numbers. He assured the Efe news agency that he had also seen several journalists with handcuffs.
The organization assures that hundreds of people have gathered here, including a delegation of religious leaders as a sign of their support for the members of the movement and for mediation with the police.
