Austria
Entry of a "Golden Budget Rule" in the Constitution
The government of the large social-democratic/Christian-democratic coalition, which is in power in Austria, decided on Tuesday to include a "Golden Budget Rule" in the constitution in order to reduce public deficits and also to avoid a possible degradation by rating agencies in the top credit rating of Austria (AAA).
It was the Social-Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann who announced this decision of the outcome of the Council of Ministers, although the public Austrian debt is 74.6%, that is, far above the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debt level of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency had not fallen from AAA to AA+ in one fell swoop, we would have to pay three billion euros in additional interest every year,” argued Michael Spindelegger, vice-chancellor and Christian Democrat foreign minister.
Austria is also making a call at the Brussels summit of the eurozone member states on 26 October: Heads of state and government at that time had demanded the inclusion of the reduction of public deficits by the end of 2012 as well as a return to the public account balance in the constitution or by enacting an equivalent law.
The measure taken by the Austrian government for this purpose is similar to the "German model", since Germany had been the first European country to include such a "rule" in the constitution.
By 2017, the structural budget deficit should decrease by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, from 2017 onwards, the state’s structural budget deficit should not exceed the 0.35% limit of GDP, whereas regional states as well as municipalities should have balanced budgets.
The objective is to eliminate budget debt under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Agreement in the 2020/21 horizon.
