Energy policy:
Facts should win over dogmas
If there is a topic that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, it is certainly energy policy.
The availability and costs of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to take an electoral meeting as an opportunity to reflect on this issue as well as on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores the total economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by the year 2050 if a huge proportion of the world’s population does not have to forgo a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources must be mitigated in order to continue to produce electricity consistently, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to fight against climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is neither the case in Belgium, which submits its decision to the need to find a substitute source capable of substitution, nor in Switzerland, which only intends to build last-generation nuclear power plants.
Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima, has decided to add another unit to its park by recommissioning the Three Mile Island plant, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Although the German model, which focuses on renewable energy sources, is occasionally presented as a model, reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, especially from Russia, as a result of the increased use of imported gas, and an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal-fired power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives cause for reflection.
On the one hand, Denmark is the European leader in terms of wind energy, from which it obtains 30% of its electricity, on the other hand, it is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, alternately used with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
As the price of energy is a key competitive factor in the globalised economy and a guarantee of stability for industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage due to the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore result in a sharp increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys have shown that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are just as unwilling to pay as it shows resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Recall that our country’s energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a plethora of specialized small and medium-sized companies to the international markets and makes them creators of countless jobs.
If France were to decide to leave nuclear power, it would fall victim to a large part of these SMEs and the annual €6 billion in capital goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink more and more.
Which electrician would commission an EPR designed to function for sixty years if the decline of its producer is pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energetic equation, one must admit that there is no such thing as a work of the devil as a miracle means of generating electricity.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy demonstrate the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a safety authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent checks in existing plants, such as the construction site in Flamanville.
Their work teams, which have made a name for themselves due to their professionalism, are just too obsessed with the idea of security.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, in Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; thus it went on without consequences for man and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was evoked by reactor construction as well as human error.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented proportions, which caused the deaths of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident as much as it did from the previous two.
As a result of this approach and a cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR is a draft that enables it to withstand such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a stop at Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF by giving them the freedom to take the leading position in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is imperative and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party manoeuvres dominate a debate that determines our country’s economic, social and financial situation as well.
