Recently, the harassment directed at foreign students by the authorities had shaped the newsreels, the Minister of the Interior had casually announced (see Libération of 23 May) that France "needed no talents, bricklayers or waiters from abroad".
But this policy has rarely been analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right was the tone of Jacques Chirac, who in 1976 declared that "900,000 unemployed people, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", on the left by Michel Rocard, who in 1990 had stated that France "cannot absorb all the poverty in the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
The fear of the invasion of national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was divided in 2005 both from the right and from the left.
From both camps, the immigrants were perceived as a burden for the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity one is willing to admit to immigrants.
Francois Hollande’s program is limited to banalities that indicate that partnership development allows us to solve our “migration problems”.
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, can potentially affect the elections; however, it is economically costly.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron remind us in a recent paper that summarizes the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of the migrant flood on economic growth, wages and jobs.
Restricting immigration would undermine growth and harm the labour market.
Concerns about migrants’ influence are based on the idea that they threaten to substitute the local workforce, especially the less skilled, by exerting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than local wage workers, as they are mainly engaged in occupations in sectors that are technically unworkable.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract much local wage workers, the more skilled among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not aligned with the labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, this complementarity between locals and migrants also has a positive effect on the influx of immigrants on wages and domestic labour market conditions.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants leads to an inclusive, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas introduced by immigrants is conducive to economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute to the welfare system net, in European countries an average of about 1% of the total budget.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that a person immigrating to Germany at the age of 30 earns a net contribution (revenue minus expenses) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget over his lifetime on average.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to bring about the missing intersections "with the teeth" at the start of his mandate.
However, these said teeth, which were intended to deter immigrants, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
