The construction of this gas transmission line is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with a concrete jacket, which is supposed to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at a depth of about 200 m.
During its construction, minefields dating from the Second World War had to be avoided.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long line of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted by anything over its entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers refrained from doing so, as the Swedes had little desire to see a Russian state company settle permanently at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller said.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas transmission line thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered by the designers as little likely, since the weld seams were estimated to have a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes from a seagoing vessel and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, with a diameter of one meter, is introduced into the interior of the pipeline and moved by the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on its arrival about any deformations of the metal.
The gas transmission line has been designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entry point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to realize this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated here (both 15.5%), as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (both 9%).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas transmission line.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company the entire capacity of its gas transport, namely on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real amount of gas transported is," said Jens Müller.
The financing of the gas pipeline construction was secured to 30% by shareholders and to 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the total investment was 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are determined to recoup their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea on a sandy, pine-covered stretch of coast near Lubmin.
The 4.5 metre high valves form the gas outlet gates.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other parameters of the incoming gas before it is forwarded to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal will be supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Launched by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give writing a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, hours spent by candlelight with writing.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognisable again, with its black rectangular cover, elastic band, eggshell pages, as if aged over time.
The Moleskine notebook, as it is known today, was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, the company’s specialist consultant at the time, is tasked with launching the new product on the market.
The notebook was inspired by an ancient production technique called mole skin, which refers to a cotton bag used, for example, for upholstery benches.
This type of notebook was in high demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine revived an old and almost forgotten object that was considered an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success is coming.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established themselves with sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to make a phantom picture of the buyers, as the notebook inspires businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded clients.
The small Italian company, which in its early days had 12 employees, now employs more than 100 people and has had two offices since 2008; one in Milan, the other in New York.
The company sells its notebooks in bookstores, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques of the city centers and knows how to assert its identity.
“We have followed the spirit of the times and its new writing needs, which exist despite the upsurge of emails,” said Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the Moleskine company: recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour (detour) " in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard print cover on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine benefited from its success and this cultural zeitgeist and knew how to diversify its products: bags, calendars, fillers, computer cases... The brand has the full range of articles.
In the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, and thus opened a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today begins the "15th week of work for the disabled".
Despite a purposeful public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is always twice the average: 19% against 9% of the total population.
Disheartening?
"No," emphasizes <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, which organizes the "week of work for the disabled."
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not double, but three times as high."
"Nevertheless, there is still an enormous amount of work to be done."
However, it must be said that many obstacles remain for disabled unemployed people before they get a job.
The elderly are more often affected: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them do not have a high school diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled students among the 2.3 million students with higher education.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% for disabled people, compared with 38% for the overall average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter work and that form the "core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 that helps companies to recruit disabled workers.
So much for the factual brakes.
The unspoken remains the unspoken, the attitudes which, while certain, are slowly developing.
A study conducted in April by the Association IMS-Entreprendre for the journal La Cité stated that the managers surveyed had “a weak level of knowledge regarding the disabled” that was “overrepresented by persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disadvantaged”.
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% disabled workers, which was laid down in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, dating from 2008, point to a 2.6% ratio.
“We are now at around 3%,” said Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the organization tasked with collecting contributions from companies that violate this law.
The proof is that the number of "fees paid" permanent establishments, as well as the sum of the sums paid in between 2007 and 2011, decreased from 59,000 to 46,000 (from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which provides for increases in contributions, created strong pressure on the companies," said Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also expresses a real insight, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of the workplaces between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
Hazard: "What happiness"
Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens had not hidden the pleasure that the friendly brought them, even before they faced the Blue Tuesday evenings (8:45 p.m.).
It would be too far-fetched to say that there was a secret agreement between them, but the picture speaks symbolic volumes.
Sitting side by side on the spectator stage of the Stade de France, George Leekens and Eden Hazard could well have made peace.
Five months after the spirited gesture of his attacking player against Turkey, the Belgian national coach had earned nothing but praise for his person.
"I am very pleased with Eden, his progress and the fact that he is a Belgian".
"I want to look forward," assures the native Liller, for his part.
As for the contrast between his representation in the club and the national team, "It is a unity that justifies everything."
"In Lille I am all year round, which is not the case in Belgium".
"It's time for me to get started".
Hazard will come to Saint-Denis, brought on Friday night against Romania regarding the match against France, to finally "shine".
However, without neglecting the note of "pleasure".
He has been supporting the French national team since the age of 7, leading his victorious campaigns between 1998 and 2000.
“I was always supported,” he confirmed.
This inevitably helps to reinforce even more the "unique" character of this encounter.
So much in advance: "Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami) will be there," he recalls.
"We just walked across the road".
"To play against them means great luck!"
Leekens, for his part, sounded "proud" with good-naturedness.
"The Pride of Performing a Galamatch".
"Proud" also to confirm - in his capacity as "neighbors" - that France "has again become a team at a very high level", and that little more than a year after the trauma of Knysna.
"Laurent Blanc did a damn good job," he said enthusiastically.
Although Belgium will be missing in the next European Championship, the technician sees very well the plane with the Blue (the French national team) share ... and namely towards Brazil in 2014.
"We little Belgians are coming out big," he stressed.
“We’re in the process of planning one thing, the players are ambitious, they’re hungry.”
"You will notice this in the upcoming games". The match against France included.
Portugal very confident
The Portuguese team of Paulo Bento is looking forward with great optimism to the return match against Bosnia (22:00) this Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the first leg, both teams lacked objectivity.
"At the end of these 90 minutes, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country".
Paulo Bento already sees himself in Poland and Ukraine.
For him, there is not the slightest hint of doubt that "La Selec<0xC3><0xA7>ao", his national team, for which he has been responsible since September 2010, will qualify for the 2012 European Championship.
For Portugal, this means in fact only 90 minutes of bliss.
